Now, **if you wanted to do it the way I did it, here is what I'd tell you to do:**

I recommend starting out by getting a magazine or two. I get mine from Barnes n Noble and  [free subscriptions like Vogue that I cancel before having to pay but right after they send me the free tote.](https://www.vogue.com/v2/offers/voga01064?source=Site_0_VOG_EDT_VOG_TICKER_BANNER_RUNWAY_0_RUNWAY_CONTROL_01059_ZZ)

I know the big magazines people still recognize try to get people to buy into their subscriptions by telling them they will get *free stuff*. Well, *I* saw this ad on Instagram one lazy summer morning and decided I needed to get every free thing they were offering. And by *they*, I mean EVERY major magazine that looked halfway like art. So I did: I bought subscriptions to GQ, Vogue, Vanity Fair, New York Times, The New Yorker, National Geographic, InStyle, and Bazaar. And after I sold my soul to anything that prints, I got up and made myself breakfast.

**Now, if you want to be a dick like me**, and you've already signed up but have NOT gotten your well deserved complementary tote, you can email them about the problem and they will fix it. Here's me outting myself for doing just that:

![tote](IMG_0268.jpeg)

For reference, that blacked out part from *Carlos* says "to your bored Karen ass". Which, by the way, is totally okay. Just remember: **it's okay to be a Karen if it's in the name of arts and crafts.**

**Next on the list of "things to get"**, go buy a [big sketchbook.](https://www.publix.com/pd/ucreate-drawing-paper-premium-sketch/RIO-PCI-597990) Trust me--it takes up more space than you'd expect. I got this sketchbook at a Publix on vacation and it's perfect: thick paper, lots of pages, and a spinal bind. Everything that makes it easy to get messy with. You can find these just about anywhere.

**Now it's time for the stickies!** I sometimes use hot glue, but tape is the easiest. I am a *little* particular about my tape. I'd say the best way to see which one works for you is to get a [bundle.](https://www.walmart.com/ip/Scotch-Tape-Variety-Pack-4122-SHDS-SR/15254204731?classType=REGULAR&from=/search&sourceid=dsn_gdn_2005b0c9-e4c7-4f46-8aaa-443883a5e447&veh=dsn&wmlspartner=dsn_gdn_2005b0c9-e4c7-4f46-8aaa-443883a5e447&cn=00c3_fy27_mp_mp_lo_int_dis_pmax-main&vtcWeb=YgUBucITT7tObaidoJrw7s&expiryTime=1770154030920&c=mWebSmartBanner) It also makes it fun to have some variety. Just don't do what I did and wear a sweater while trying out the different tapes--I used double sided tape and didn't realize it and my sweater unraveled a bit and became part of the scrapbook. But don't worry--I made it a fuzzy spread and pretended it was intentional.

If you don't want to risk it, or if your outfit HAS to pair with a sweater, get [hot glue.](https://www.hobbylobby.com/floral-wedding/floral-supplies/wire-tools/purple---mini-low-temp-hot-glue-gun/p/4676) I got mine at Hobby Lobby on a whim in the checkout line and it was the **best purchase I ever made**. I don’t think it was made to withstand the amount of glue I have demanded it to melt, but it hasn’t failed me yet.

**You can get content from just about anything printed.** You can use old neglected books, maps, receipts, flyers, newspapers, etc! You can also use even randomer things like the stickers you peel off your fruits, box graphics from frozen meals, stamps from letters, teabag tags, or expired coupons. Gobblerfest, an event that takes place at Virginia Tech, is where I got the most free stuff for scrapbooking on campus. Pretend to be interested in everything, get free pretty flyers and stickers, then go back and rip it all up to make a spread on what it felt like to date your ex. 

**Content can be found anywhere: even on the road!** 

I would argue that **the best environment to scrapbook in is on a road trip.**  There’s touring magazines, maps, free newspapers at gas stations, and all sorts of stuff that keep it random. It’s also a fun way to keep tickets, receipts–things that would otherwise be thrown away but could be made pretty when put with other things. Here's an example of a spread I made when I went down to the Everglades with a friend.

![[Florida Scrapbook]](IMG_8698-1.jpeg)

I loved making this because scrapbooking does not care about the environment you're working in. It can work in any setting with any type of person. That is, unless, you're scrapbooking near a scrapbook hater. In that case, I suggest you get better friends.

As someone with *spicy* ADHD, scrapbooking is satisfying on *so* many levels. **You can do however many things you want all at once without actually doing anything other than scrapbooking.** I will tear things out of magazines to use on a variety of pages that each cover different things. Half my scrapbook have individual page themes, while the others are theories and thoughts on shows I binge with my friends. There are even other pages trying to dissect my life, and ones that are just things I thought would look pretty together. Sometimes I have intentional, or "intentional", ugly pages. In those, I try to make it as horrible to look at as possible. If you make an ugly page, show it to your scrapbook hater friend to set them off.

I'd say **the most satisfying part though is watching the sketchbook bloat and threaten to fall apart.** Mine did fall apart, and I got creative (as I do) and tried to tie it all together with the red string my roommate was using to make a crazy theory board with. I did get her permission, don't worry.

Anddd **those are my two cents on scrapbooking!!** (rip the penny) I impromptly sprinkled in some details about art and the making of it that *you* didn’t ask for, and you're welcome. Thank you for reading (;

